<h2>History</h2>
<p>
  First held in Delaware in 1998, Teach Children to Save Day (TCTSD) is part of a nationwide
  financial literacy effort that works to educate elementary school students throughout Delaware on
  the importance of saving as the basis for future financial security.  Through the program, children
  are encouraged from a young age to develop the habits that will help ensure their future economic
  independence.
</p>
<p>
  The impact on students reached has been significant. With over 350 third and fourth grade
  classrooms participating each year. Teach Children to Save Day lessons have reached more than
  140,000 students since the program's inception 16 years ago.
</p>

<h2>The Program</h2>
<p>
  Teach Children to Save Day is offered through a partnership of the University of Delaware Center
  for Economic Education and Entrepreneurship (CEEE) and the Delaware Bankers Association Financial
  Education Alliance (DBA/FEA).  Offered over three days in April, volunteer bankers visit schools
  throughout Delaware to read a book and teach a lesson on the importance of saving, the basics of
  financial education, and the benefits of prudent money management.
</p>
<p>
  TCTSD has several components.
</p>
<ul class="not_red">
  <li><span>Lesson&mdash;Delaware bank volunteers teach third and fourth grade students using a children’s
    book written by Greg Koseluk of the DBA and a lesson developed by the CEEE.</span></li>
  <li><span>Proclamation Signing&mdash;The Governor declares the week Teach Children to Save Week signing
    the proclamation at a local elementary school.</span></li>
  <li><span>Training&mdash;An on-line video provides training for volunteers, showing an experienced
    educator teaching the lesson and offering helpful classroom tips.</span></li>
  <li><span>Book&mdash;Each classroom receives a copy of the TCTSD book for the classroom’s library.</span></li>
  <li><span>Take Away&mdash;Each child receives a fun-filled activity book with important messages
    on saving to share with their families.</span></li>
  <li><span>Poster Contest&mdash;All participating students are eligible to enter a poster contest
    designing a poster on saving. The first place winner receives $100.</span></li>
</ul>

<h2>Accolades</h2>
<p>
  Delaware's Teach Children to Save Day program has consistently been recognized as one of the best
  in the nation by the American Bankers Association.
</p>
